function expandCh1() {
  let ch = book.chapters[0].content;
  ch = appendToChapter(ch, `
<h2>1.6 The Research Mindset in Professional Practice</h2>
<p>The research mindset is not confined to universities and laboratories. It is increasingly recognised as a critical professional competency across virtually every industry. In medicine, evidence-based practice has transformed patient care by insisting that clinical decisions be informed by the best available research evidence, combined with clinical expertise and patient values. In education, the movement toward evidence-informed teaching has encouraged teachers to evaluate pedagogical strategies with the same rigour that scientists apply to laboratory experiments.</p>
<p>In the business world, the rise of data-driven decision-making reflects the same fundamental shift. Companies like Google, Amazon, and Netflix have built their competitive advantages on the systematic collection and analysis of data - essentially, on research thinking applied to commercial problems. When Netflix decides which shows to commission, it does not rely solely on the intuition of entertainment executives. It analyses viewing patterns, completion rates, genre preferences, and demographic data to make informed decisions. This is research thinking in action, even though it occurs outside a traditional academic setting.</p>
<p>The implications for your career are significant. Whatever field you enter, the ability to think like a researcher - to evaluate evidence critically, to design systematic investigations, to draw conclusions that are proportionate to the data - will distinguish you from colleagues who rely solely on experience, intuition, or tradition. This is not to say that experience and intuition are valueless. They are essential. But they are most powerful when combined with the disciplined habits of research thinking.</p>
<p>Consider the healthcare administrator who must decide whether to implement a new patient safety protocol. Without research thinking, they might adopt the protocol because it sounds reasonable, because a charismatic colleague recommended it, or because it is being used at a prestigious institution. With research thinking, they would ask: What evidence supports this protocol? Were the studies conducted in similar settings? What are the implementation costs and potential risks? Are there alternative approaches with stronger evidence? These questions do not guarantee a perfect decision, but they dramatically increase the probability of a good one.</p>
<p>The same principle applies to policy-making, social work, engineering, law, and every other profession where decisions have consequences. The research-minded professional does not simply accept the status quo or defer to authority. They ask for evidence, evaluate its quality, and make decisions based on the best available information. This is not a luxury - in an increasingly complex world, it is a necessity.</p>

<h2>1.7 Developing Research Thinking: A Lifelong Journey</h2>
<p>Research thinking is not a skill you acquire once and possess forever. It is a practice that deepens over time through continuous engagement with ideas, evidence, and scholarly conversation. Like any sophisticated skill - playing a musical instrument, speaking a foreign language, practising surgery - it requires sustained effort, regular practice, and a willingness to learn from mistakes.</p>
<p>The early stages of developing research thinking are often the most challenging. You are learning a new language - the language of methodology, theory, and evidence-based reasoning. You are developing new habits of mind - questioning assumptions, seeking disconfirming evidence, tolerating ambiguity. And you are doing all of this while simultaneously trying to master the content of your specific discipline. It is no wonder that many students feel overwhelmed during their first year of graduate study.</p>
<p>But the rewards of persisting through this initial discomfort are substantial. As your research thinking skills develop, you begin to see the world differently. You notice assumptions that were previously invisible. You recognise logical fallacies in arguments that once seemed persuasive. You develop the ability to evaluate competing claims and form your own evidence-based positions. This transformation is not just intellectually satisfying - it is practically valuable in every domain of life.</p>
<p>The journey of developing research thinking also involves learning to manage the emotional dimensions of scholarly work. Research is not a purely cognitive activity. It involves frustration when experiments fail, anxiety when presenting your work to critical audiences, disappointment when your hypothesis is not supported, and joy when you discover something genuinely new. Learning to navigate these emotions - to persevere through frustration, to view criticism as a gift rather than an attack, to find motivation in the process rather than just the outcome - is an essential part of becoming a mature researcher.</p>
<p>Perhaps most importantly, developing research thinking teaches you intellectual humility. The more you learn about the complexity of any topic, the more you appreciate how much you do not know. This humility is not weakness - it is the foundation of genuine expertise. The researcher who acknowledges the limits of their knowledge is far more credible than the one who claims certainty where none exists. And the professional who admits uncertainty while actively seeking better evidence is far more effective than the one who clings to outdated practices because they cannot admit that their knowledge might be incomplete.</p>

<h2>1.8 The Ethical Dimension of Research Thinking</h2>
<p>Research thinking carries with it an ethical responsibility. When you claim to know something based on evidence, you are making a promise to your audience - a promise that you have investigated carefully, evaluated honestly, and reported faithfully. This promise is the foundation of trust in scholarship, and violating it has consequences that extend far beyond the individual researcher.</p>
<p>The history of research is marked by episodes where this trust was violated - from the fabrication of data in medical research that led to harmful treatments, to the selective reporting of drug trial results that concealed dangerous side effects, to the plagiarism scandals that have ended promising careers. These violations are not just personal failings; they are attacks on the integrity of the knowledge system that all of us depend on.</p>
<p>As you develop your research thinking skills, you are also developing an ethical sensibility - a commitment to honesty, transparency, and rigour that should guide all of your scholarly work. This means reporting findings accurately, even when they contradict your expectations. It means acknowledging the limitations of your methods and the boundaries of your conclusions. It means giving proper credit to the ideas and work of others. And it means treating research participants with respect and dignity, ensuring that the pursuit of knowledge never comes at the expense of human welfare.</p>
<p>These ethical commitments are not optional extras that you add to your research after the intellectual work is done. They are woven into the fabric of research thinking itself. A study that reaches the right conclusion through dishonest means is not good research - it is lucky dishonesty. And a researcher who produces impressive results through unethical methods is not a good researcher - they are a fraud who has not yet been caught. The integration of intellectual rigour and ethical commitment is what distinguishes true scholarship from mere cleverness.</p>
`);
  book.chapters[0].content = ch;
}

