function expandCh2() {
  let ch = book.chapters[1].content;
  ch = appendToChapter(ch, `
<h2>2.5 The Role of Reading in Sustaining Curiosity</h2>
<p>Reading is the single most important activity for sustaining scholarly curiosity. But the kind of reading that feeds research curiosity is different from the reading most people do in their daily lives. It is active, questioning, and purposeful. When you read a research article with a researcher's eye, you are not passively absorbing information - you are engaging in a dialogue with the author, questioning their assumptions, evaluating their evidence, and considering how their findings relate to what you already know.</p>
<p>Effective scholarly reading involves multiple passes through a text. The first pass might be a quick scan to determine whether the article is relevant to your interests. The second pass involves a more careful reading of the introduction, methods, and conclusions to understand the study's contribution. The third pass - reserved for the most important articles - involves a detailed, critical analysis of the argument, the methodology, and the interpretation of results. This multi-pass approach is far more efficient than trying to read every article in detail, and it ensures that you invest your deepest attention where it will yield the greatest return.</p>
<p>Cross-disciplinary reading deserves special emphasis. Some of the most important research breakthroughs have come from scholars who applied ideas from one field to problems in another. The psychologist Daniel Kahneman, for example, revolutionised economics by applying insights from cognitive psychology to economic decision-making - work that earned him the Nobel Prize in Economics. The biologist Lynn Margulis transformed our understanding of evolution by applying insights from microbiology to questions about how complex cells evolved. In both cases, the breakthrough came from reading outside the researcher's primary discipline and recognising connections that specialists within each field had missed.</p>
<p>To cultivate this kind of productive cross-disciplinary reading, consider allocating a portion of your reading time - perhaps ten to twenty per cent - to journals, books, and articles outside your immediate field. Read broadly in related disciplines, attend interdisciplinary seminars, and pay attention to methodology sections in studies from other fields. You may not find immediate applications, but over time, you will develop a broader perspective that enriches your own research and opens up possibilities that more narrowly focused scholars might miss.</p>

<h2>2.6 Curiosity in the Digital Age</h2>
<p>The digital revolution has transformed the landscape of scholarly curiosity in profound and sometimes contradictory ways. On one hand, digital technologies have made access to information easier than at any time in human history. Databases like Google Scholar, PubMed, and JSTOR provide instant access to millions of research articles. Preprint servers make cutting-edge research available before formal peer review. Social media platforms like Twitter and ResearchGate allow scholars to share ideas and discuss findings in real time, creating a global conversation that was impossible a generation ago.</p>
<p>On the other hand, the sheer volume of available information can be overwhelming, and the algorithms that curate our digital feeds can narrow rather than broaden our intellectual horizons. When search engines and recommendation systems show you more of what you have already shown interest in, they create intellectual echo chambers that reinforce existing beliefs rather than challenging them. The curious researcher must actively resist this tendency by deliberately seeking out diverse perspectives, unfamiliar methodologies, and findings that challenge their assumptions.</p>
<p>Digital tools can also accelerate the process of narrowing from broad curiosity to focused research questions. Citation mapping tools like Scopus, Web of Science, and Connected Papers allow you to visualise the intellectual landscape of a topic, identifying key papers, influential authors, and emerging trends. Reference management software like Zotero, Mendeley, and EndNote helps you organise and annotate the literature you collect. And collaborative platforms like Overleaf and Google Docs make it easier to work with co-authors and supervisors in real time.</p>
<p>However, digital tools are means, not ends. They can support and accelerate scholarly curiosity, but they cannot create it. The fundamental drivers of curiosity - a genuine desire to understand, a willingness to question, an openness to surprise - are human qualities that no algorithm can replicate. The most effective researchers are those who combine the power of digital tools with the irreplaceable human capacities of wonder, creativity, and critical judgement.</p>

<h2>2.7 Barriers to Curiosity and How to Overcome Them</h2>
<p>Despite its obvious value, scholarly curiosity faces numerous barriers that can suppress or extinguish it if left unaddressed. Understanding these barriers is the first step toward overcoming them.</p>
<p>The most common barrier is fear of looking ignorant. In academic culture, there is often an implicit pressure to appear knowledgeable at all times. Asking a basic question in a seminar, admitting that you do not understand a key concept, or confessing that you have not read an important paper can feel deeply embarrassing. But this fear is profoundly counterproductive, because it prevents you from asking the very questions that would deepen your understanding. The most successful researchers are those who have learned to ask freely, to admit ignorance without shame, and to view every gap in their knowledge as an opportunity for learning rather than a source of embarrassment.</p>
<p>A second barrier is the pressure to specialise too early. Academic careers increasingly reward deep specialisation, which can discourage the broad reading and interdisciplinary exploration that feeds curiosity. While specialisation is necessary and valuable, it should not come at the expense of intellectual breadth. The researcher who reads only within their narrow subfield risks missing important connections and becoming unable to communicate with scholars in related areas.</p>
<p>A third barrier is the institutional pressure to produce. The publish-or-perish culture of modern academia can push researchers toward safe, incremental studies rather than the ambitious, curiosity-driven investigations that produce genuine breakthroughs. When your career depends on a steady stream of publications, the temptation to pursue small, guaranteed results rather than large, uncertain ones can be overwhelming. Overcoming this barrier requires institutional reform, but it also requires individual courage - the willingness to pursue important questions even when they do not guarantee quick publications.</p>
<p>A fourth barrier is burnout. Research is intellectually demanding work, and the combination of long hours, high expectations, and uncertain outcomes can drain even the most enthusiastic scholar of their curiosity and motivation. Protecting your curiosity requires protecting your well-being: maintaining boundaries between work and rest, cultivating relationships and interests outside academia, and seeking support when you feel overwhelmed. Curiosity thrives in a rested, balanced mind - not in one that is exhausted and anxious.</p>
`);
  book.chapters[1].content = ch;
}

