function expandCh5() {
  let ch = book.chapters[4].content;
  ch = appendToChapter(ch, `
<h2>5.5 The Relationship Between Research Questions and Methodology</h2>
<p>The relationship between your research question and your methodology is intimate and reciprocal. Your question determines which methods are appropriate, and your choice of methods constrains what questions you can answer. Understanding this relationship is essential for designing research that is both coherent and productive.</p>
<p>Descriptive questions - those that ask "What is the nature of X?" - typically call for methods that allow rich, detailed observation. Surveys can describe the distribution of attitudes or behaviours across a population. Ethnographic observation can describe the culture and practices of a specific group. Content analysis can describe patterns in texts or media. The choice among these methods depends on what specifically you want to describe and the kind of detail you need.</p>
<p>Relational questions - those that ask "Is X associated with Y?" - typically require methods that allow you to measure both variables and examine the statistical relationship between them. Correlational studies, regression analyses, and structural equation models are common approaches. However, it is crucial to remember that relational methods can establish association but not causation. Just because two variables are correlated does not mean that one causes the other.</p>
<p>Causal questions - those that ask "Does X cause Y?" - require the most rigorous methods, ideally experimental or quasi-experimental designs that control for confounding variables. Randomised controlled trials (RCTs) are considered the gold standard for establishing causation because random assignment ensures that the treatment and control groups are equivalent at baseline, allowing any subsequent differences to be attributed to the treatment rather than to pre-existing differences between groups.</p>
<p>Interpretive questions - those that ask "What does X mean to participants?" - require qualitative methods that allow you to explore subjective experiences in depth. In-depth interviews, focus groups, phenomenological analysis, and narrative inquiry are common approaches. These methods do not seek to quantify or generalise but to understand - to capture the richness and complexity of human experience in ways that quantitative methods cannot.</p>

<h2>5.6 Common Pitfalls in Research Question Formulation</h2>
<p>Even experienced researchers sometimes formulate research questions that are flawed in ways that become apparent only after significant time and effort have been invested. Learning to recognise these pitfalls early can save you months of frustration and wasted work.</p>
<p>One common pitfall is the assumption-laden question. This is a question that contains an embedded assumption that has not been tested. For example, "Why do students prefer online learning to face-to-face instruction?" assumes that students do prefer online learning, which may or may not be true. A better approach would be to first ask whether students prefer online learning (a descriptive question) and only then, if the answer is yes, to ask why (an explanatory question).</p>
<p>Another pitfall is the tautological question - a question whose answer is contained in its definition. For example, "Do motivated students perform better academically?" is tautological if motivation is defined in terms of academic effort and engagement, because by definition, motivated students are those who try harder. To avoid tautology, ensure that your key concepts are defined independently of each other and that your question genuinely investigates a relationship rather than restating a definition.</p>
<p>A third pitfall is the unfocused question. This is a question that tries to investigate too many variables, populations, or contexts at once. "How do socioeconomic status, parental education, peer influence, teacher quality, and school resources interact to affect the academic achievement of primary school students in urban, suburban, and rural settings across three countries?" is a question so complex that no single study could address it adequately. Focus on the most important variables and the most relevant context, and leave the rest for future studies.</p>
<p>A fourth pitfall is the question that cannot be answered with available methods or data. Before committing to a research question, verify that appropriate methods exist, that you have the skills and resources to use them, and that the data you need can realistically be collected. A brilliant question that cannot be investigated is an exercise in frustration, not a research project.</p>

<h2>5.7 Research Questions Across Disciplines</h2>
<p>Research questions take different forms in different disciplines, reflecting the different epistemological assumptions, methodological traditions, and practical concerns of each field. Understanding these disciplinary variations is important for two reasons: it helps you formulate questions that are appropriate for your own field, and it enables you to read and evaluate research from other fields more effectively.</p>
<p>In the natural sciences, research questions are often framed as hypotheses - testable predictions about the relationship between variables. "If we increase the concentration of nitrogen fertiliser, then crop yield will increase up to a threshold, after which it will decrease." This hypothesis-driven approach reflects the positivist epistemology of the natural sciences, which seeks to discover general laws through controlled experimentation.</p>
<p>In the social sciences, research questions are more diverse. Quantitative social scientists often use hypothesis-driven approaches similar to those in the natural sciences. Qualitative social scientists typically frame broader, more open-ended questions: "How do first-generation university students experience the transition to higher education?" Mixed-methods researchers may combine both approaches, using qualitative methods to explore a phenomenon and quantitative methods to test specific aspects of what they have discovered.</p>
<p>In the humanities, research questions are often interpretive or critical in nature. "How does Shakespeare's use of imagery in Hamlet reflect Elizabethan anxieties about political succession?" This question does not seek to discover a general law or test a hypothesis. It seeks to deepen understanding of a specific text within its historical and cultural context.</p>
<p>In professional disciplines like medicine, engineering, education, and business, research questions are often driven by practical problems. "Does early mobilisation after hip replacement surgery reduce length of hospital stay and improve functional outcomes?" This question is motivated by a practical need to improve patient care, and its answer will directly inform clinical practice.</p>
`);
  book.chapters[4].content = ch;
}

